    content: `<h2>Your Assessment: How Does Collins Present Power in The Hunger Games?</h2>
<p>This module prepares you for your end-of-unit assessment. You will write an analytical essay responding to the question: <strong>"How does Collins present the theme of power in <em>The Hunger Games</em>?"</strong> This assessment draws together everything you have learned: your understanding of the text, your analytical skills, your ability to embed quotations, and your command of written expression.</p>

<h3>Understanding the Question</h3>
<p>Let us break the question down using the skills from Module 1:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Command word: "How"</strong> — You must explain the <em>methods</em> Collins uses. This means discussing techniques, word choices, structural decisions, and their effects. You are not asked <em>what</em> power is in the novel — you are asked <em>how</em> it is presented.</li>
<li><strong>Focus: "the theme of power"</strong> — Every point must connect to power. If a paragraph discusses a character or event without linking it to power, it is not answering the question.</li>
<li><strong>Writer focus: "Collins"</strong> — The question asks about the <em>writer's</em> choices. Use phrases like "Collins presents," "Collins suggests," "Collins uses" to keep the writer visible in your answer.</li>
</ul>

<div class="key-term"><strong>Key Term: Writer's methods</strong> — The deliberate choices a writer makes about language, structure, form, and narrative perspective. When a question asks "how," it is asking about methods. These include word choice, imagery, symbolism, structure, narrative voice, and literary techniques.</div>

<h3>Planning Your Essay</h3>
<p>Before writing a single word of your essay, spend 5-8 minutes planning. A planned essay is always better than an unplanned one, even if the plan costs you some writing time.</p>

<h4>Suggested Plan Structure:</h4>
<ol>
<li><strong>Introduction (2-3 sentences):</strong> State your overarching argument about how Collins presents power. Do not waste time on biography or plot summary.</li>
<li><strong>Paragraph 1: Power through spectacle and entertainment</strong> — The Games as televised violence, euphemistic language ("the Games," "tributes"), the transformation of murder into entertainment.</li>
<li><strong>Paragraph 2: Power through economic control and inequality</strong> — The tesserae system, district-Capitol resource extraction, food as weapon and symbol.</li>
<li><strong>Paragraph 3: Power through language and narrative control</strong> — Euphemism, propaganda, naming, the Capitol's control of the story through media.</li>
<li><strong>Paragraph 4: Power challenged — resistance and defiance</strong> — The three-finger salute, Rue's flowers, the berries. How Collins shows that power, however total, can be resisted.</li>
<li><strong>Conclusion (2-3 sentences):</strong> Synthesise your argument. What is Collins's overall message about power?</li>
</ol>

<div class="examiner-tip"><strong>Exam Strategy:</strong> Your introduction should be short and sharp. Do not begin with "In this essay I will discuss..." Instead, begin with your argument: "Collins presents power in <em>The Hunger Games</em> as a force that operates through spectacle, economic exploitation, and linguistic manipulation, ultimately suggesting that the most dangerous form of power is the kind that makes its own violence invisible."</div>

<h3>Assessment Criteria: What Gets High Marks</h3>
<p>Your essay will be assessed on four areas:</p>

<h4>1. Understanding and Response (AO1)</h4>
<ul>
<li>Do you understand the text and the question?</li>
<li>Is your response focused on the theme of power throughout?</li>
<li>Do you use well-chosen evidence (short, embedded quotations)?</li>
</ul>

<h4>2. Analysis of Writer's Methods (AO2)</h4>
<ul>
<li>Do you identify specific techniques (euphemism, symbolism, narrative voice, juxtaposition)?</li>
<li>Do you explain the <em>effect</em> of these techniques, not just name them?</li>
<li>Do you use the "This suggests... because..." formula to develop your analysis?</li>
</ul>

<h4>3. Context and Connections (AO3)</h4>
<ul>
<li>Do you connect the novel's themes to relevant contexts (Roman history, reality TV, modern surveillance)?</li>
<li>Is context <em>integrated</em> into your analysis, not bolted on as a separate paragraph?</li>
</ul>

<h4>4. Written Expression (AO4)</h4>
<ul>
<li>Is your essay clearly structured with focused paragraphs?</li>
<li>Is your tense consistent (literary present for text analysis)?</li>
<li>Are your quotations embedded, not bolted on?</li>
<li>Is your vocabulary precise and ambitious?</li>
</ul>

<h3>Model Opening Paragraph</h3>
<p class="example-strong">Collins presents power in <em>The Hunger Games</em> not as a simple force wielded by strong individuals, but as a sophisticated system of control that operates through spectacle, economic exploitation, and the manipulation of language. The Capitol's dominance depends less on its military might than on its ability to make its own violence seem normal — even entertaining. Through the euphemistic framing of child murder as "the Games" and the transformation of suffering into televised spectacle, Collins suggests that the most dangerous form of power is one that convinces its victims that their oppression is simply the way things are.</p>

<h3>Common Pitfalls to Avoid</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Narrative retelling:</strong> Do not spend paragraphs summarising what happens. The examiner knows the plot. Focus on <em>how</em> and <em>why</em>.</li>
<li><strong>Feature spotting:</strong> Do not just list techniques. "Collins uses a metaphor here and a simile there" scores nothing without analysis of their effects.</li>
<li><strong>Losing focus:</strong> Every paragraph must connect to <strong>power</strong>. If you find yourself writing about a character without linking to the theme, stop and redirect.</li>
<li><strong>Bolt-on context:</strong> Do not write a separate paragraph about "context." Instead, weave contextual understanding into your analysis: "Collins's critique of the Capitol's televised violence echoes concerns about reality TV's desensitisation of modern audiences."</li>
<li><strong>Weak conclusions:</strong> Do not end with "In conclusion, Collins presents power in many ways." Instead, synthesise: "Ultimately, Collins presents power as a force that is most effective when invisible — embedded in language, normalised through spectacle, and maintained through systems that make inequality appear natural."</li>
</ul>

<div class="common-mistake"><strong>Common Mistake:</strong> Spending too long on one paragraph and running out of time. Allocate your time evenly across all paragraphs. A complete essay with four solid paragraphs scores much higher than an incomplete essay with two brilliant ones.</div>

<h3>Final Checklist Before Submitting</h3>
<ul>
<li>Does every paragraph answer the question about power?</li>
<li>Have I identified specific techniques and explained their effects?</li>
<li>Are my quotations short and embedded?</li>
<li>Have I used "This suggests... because..." at least three times?</li>
<li>Is my tense consistent (literary present for text, past for context)?</li>
<li>Does my conclusion synthesise my argument rather than just repeating it?</li>
<li>Have I proofread for spelling, punctuation, and grammar errors?</li>
</ul>`,
